Introduction¶

San Francisco is one of the most popular tourist destinations in the world and considered as a desired place to live in with its pleasant climate, progressive culture, and career opportunities. However, what is the downside of visiting or residing in SF?

I look at SF crime reports from 2003 to 2014, with a focus on the incidents of Larceny-Theft. I am interested in how the incident changes with time and district as well as how weather and unemployment influence the frequency of the incident.

The primary dataset I rely on is downloaded from Kaggle, https://www.kaggle.com/c/sf-crime/data, which includes the type, time, result, district, latitude, and longitude of the crime incidents derived from the SFPD Crime Incident Reporting System. The original crime data ranges from 1/1/2003 to 5/13/2015 and is divided into a training set and a test set, in which weeks of even number belong to the training and weeks of odd number belong to the test.

For this analysis, I only use the training set. Additionally, I exclude the data of 2015 for the purpose of exploring the crime incidents over month within a year. I also remove the observations out of the range of latitude and longitude of SF.

Furthermore, to examine the effect of unemployment rate and weather on crime incidents, I downloded the monthly unemployment data by U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics from Economic Research and scraped the daily weather data from Weather Underground API.
